109
00:05:39,919 --> 00:05:45,280
Lesson number one is learn and use version control relentlessly.

110
00:05:45,280 --> 00:05:47,360
By version control, I'm talking about Git.

111
00:05:47,360 --> 00:05:55,759
And I've used Git a lot for managing my codebase, but I think it's actually even more important when it comes to vibe coding.

112
00:05:55,759 --> 00:05:58,800
Using Git is not about saving your code.

113
00:05:58,800 --> 00:06:04,080
It's actually about giving yourself permission to break things and not feel shitty about it.

114
00:06:04,080 --> 00:06:13,039
When you know that you can revert back to a working version of your product, it unlocks a whole new confidence and creativity while you're vibe coding.

115
00:06:13,039 --> 00:06:20,479
If you want to try something tricky or totally rework something, you can do it with confidence knowing you can just revert back at any given time.

116
00:06:20,479 --> 00:06:24,080
So with this project, I treated Git like a journal.

117
00:06:24,080 --> 00:06:28,720
I basically committed up every single time I made the tiniest change possible.

118
00:06:28,720 --> 00:06:34,160
Sometimes it was a oneline change, but I never committed more than one feature to the codebase.

119
00:06:34,160 --> 00:06:37,759
And what's cool is I actually used the AI to make the commit messages.

120
00:06:37,759 --> 00:06:40,080
And it didn't take me any longer to do this.

121
00:06:40,080 --> 00:06:43,600
And it gave me a lot of confidence that I could always go back at any given time.

122
00:06:43,600 --> 00:06:48,880
So in summary, by using Git, I made changes in a much more focused, bite-sized way.

123
00:06:48,880 --> 00:06:54,240
Each commit to my project was related to a very specific feature or change that I was making.

124
00:06:54,240 --> 00:07:00,880
And this was honestly one of the easiest changes that I could make to my workflow, but it made one of the biggest differences.

125
00:07:00,880 --> 00:07:07,120
So, in summary, use Git, use it a lot, get good at it, learn how to revert, learn how to stash changes,

126
00:07:07,120 --> 00:07:08,560
and all that sort of stuff.

127
00:07:08,560 --> 00:07:20,479
